<div id="review_683460867" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/683460867" />
    <a title="Shawn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11011728-shawn"><img alt="Shawn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442516511p2/11011728.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/683460867?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shawn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shawn" href="/user/show/11011728-shawn">Shawn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780451525253" href="/book/show/659310.The_Ox_Bow_Incident">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer683460867" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6613214583224907799">A psychological western that seemed to question the basic assumption that frontier justice was hard but fair. It seemed the author wanted to paint a picture that men in groups inevitably follow a &quot;herd mentality&quot; and when someone shouts &quot;something must be done&quot;, inevitably, the wrong thing will be done. The book was well written but a tad preachy. It seemed, at times, I was reading the script of an old Twilight Zone script..still... a western literature fan should read this through once in his o</span>
  <span id="freeText6613214583224907799" style="display:none">A psychological western that seemed to question the basic assumption that frontier justice was hard but fair. It seemed the author wanted to paint a picture that men in groups inevitably follow a "herd mentality" and when someone shouts "something must be done", inevitably, the wrong thing will be done. The book was well written but a tad preachy. It seemed, at times, I was reading the script of an old Twilight Zone script..still... a western literature fan should read this through once in his or her life. It is well written and very different from other westerns from the time (early 1940s). It may be the only frontier story that beats the adage it is better for ten guilty men to go free than one innocent be convicted. I don't know...depends. I could argue society would find preferable convicting a number of innocents for traffic tickets than allow ten murderers and rapists run free. This book is great to start the mind running. I think the moral of the story is not for people stop striving for justice but to take their time in doing so. Not very Charles Bronson like but far more suited to a civilized society. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6613214583224907799" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


