<div id="review_3852542518" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3852542518" />
    <a title="Tomislav" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3082950-tomislav"><img alt="Tomislav" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640383557p2/3082950.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3852542518?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tomislav" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tomislav" href="/user/show/3082950-tomislav">Tomislav</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780451525253" href="/book/show/659310.The_Ox_Bow_Incident">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3082950-tomislav?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3852542518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4422527688083877909">15 March 2009 - It&apos;s been a long time since I read a &quot;Western&quot;, but this 1940 novel is more a psychological study of characters set in 1880s Nevada, than a cowboy story like Shane. It examines closely the relationships between the men, from a pre-feminist perspective that would probably not be possible today. The West of that time was populated primarily by men, who lived lives largely uncontrolled by the influences of civilization, and yet were still constrained by a rigid moral code. That code</span>
  <span id="freeText4422527688083877909" style="display:none">15 March 2009 - It's been a long time since I read a "Western", but this 1940 novel is more a psychological study of characters set in 1880s Nevada, than a cowboy story like Shane. It examines closely the relationships between the men, from a pre-feminist perspective that would probably not be possible today. The West of that time was populated primarily by men, who lived lives largely uncontrolled by the influences of civilization, and yet were still constrained by a rigid moral code. That code was not one of internal self-control, but one that demanded immediate and harsh correction of the frequent deviations. It is the rumor of major violations of the code - rustling and murder - that after much posturing leads to the self-appointment of a posse to pursue the perpetrators. The decision-making, and its consequent events are the drama of the story. Clark had extensive experience in theater before writing this novel, and it shows.<br /><br />Having been written at the beginning of World War 2, I think Clark's commentaries on the rule of law, and guilt by both commission and omission, relate to the rise of fascism in the world. It's a warning, as in "this is how it happens".</span>
  <a data-text-id="4422527688083877909" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


