<div id="review_95902736" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/95902736" />
    <a title="Stephen Gallup" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1266077-stephen-gallup"><img alt="Stephen Gallup" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321228329p2/1266077.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/95902736?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stephen Gallup" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stephen Gallup" href="/user/show/1266077-stephen-gallup">Stephen Gallup</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer95902736" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18290353047464690426">This book has been on the edge of my awareness for years but I never knew what it was about. Finally picked it up.<br/> <br/>The opening pages made me smile at the &quot;cowpoke speak&quot; with exchanges like the following, which takes place over the bar in an otherwise empty saloon:<br/> <br/>&quot;Well?&quot; [That&apos;s the bartender speaking:] <br/>&quot;Don&apos;t rush me,&quot; Gil said. <br/>&quot;Take your time,&quot; Canby said.<br/>&quot;It don&apos;t look to me,&quot; Gil said, &quot;like you was so rushed you couldn&apos;t wait!&quot;<br/>&quot;It&apos;s not that. I hate to see a man who can&apos;t make up his min</span>
  <span id="freeText18290353047464690426" style="display:none">This book has been on the edge of my awareness for years but I never knew what it was about. Finally picked it up.<br /> <br />The opening pages made me smile at the "cowpoke speak" with exchanges like the following, which takes place over the bar in an otherwise empty saloon:<br /> <br />"Well?" [That's the bartender speaking:] <br />"Don't rush me," Gil said. <br />"Take your time," Canby said.<br />"It don't look to me," Gil said, "like you was so rushed you couldn't wait!"<br />"It's not that. I hate to see a man who can't make up his mind."<br />"What do you care?"<br />"I either have to put them to bed or listen to their troubles, depending on what they drink," Canby said.<br />"I ain't lookin' for either sleep or comfortin'," Gil said. "And if I was, I wouldn't come here for it."<br />"I feel better," said Canby. "What'll you have? Whisky?"<br />"What have you got?"<br />"Whisky."<br />"Did you ever know such a guy?" Gil said to me. "All this time I'm thinkin', and all he's got's whisky."<br />"And that's rotten, ain't it?" he asked Canby.<br />"Rotten," Canby agreed.<br />"Two glasses and a bottle," Gil said.<br /> <br />At that point, I was recalling a friend who used to write fairly predictable <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5110706-death-on-the-texas-range" rel="nofollow noopener">Western potboilers</a>, and so was taken by surprise when things abruptly veered in an unexpected direction. Somebody has been killed offstage and, even though it's all hearsay and nobody knew the victim well, almost everybody is eager to go find some culprit(s) and string them up. Voices of dissent are not welcome, but a few of the fellows persist in attempting a reasoned dialog:<br /> <br />"What would you say real justice was, Bill?"<br />Winder got cautious. "Whadya mean?" he asked.<br />"I mean, if you had to say what justice was, how would you put it?"<br />"It sure as hell ain't lettin' things go till any sneakin' cattle thief can shoot a man down and only get a laugh out of it. It ain't that, anyway," he defended.<br />"No, it certainly isn't that," Davies agreed.<br />"It's seeing everybody gets what's comin' to him, that's what it is," Winder said.<br />"But according to whom?" Davies asked him. "Who decides what everybody's got coming to him?"<br />Winder looked at us, daring us to grin. "We do," he said belligerantly.<br />"Who are we?"<br />"Who the hell would we be? The rest of us. The straight ones."<br /> <br />At first, I thought this was turning into a morality tale about mob rule (the sort of phenomenon best illustrated by China's Cultural Revolution, of which my wife is a survivor), but after more than 100 pages of somewhat tedious arguments pro and con, including at least one point at which most members of the self-appointed posse seem ready to give up their plan as a bad idea, only to swing into action once again when prodded by somebody with clout, I decided that what it truly resembles is the way the U.S. government now operates.<br /> <br />That impression was borne out through the rest of the book, because it would be hard to say this is a story about impetuous action. Deep thought is not often on display, but the characters argue incessantly throughout all that happens next, and in the aftermath, when they wrestle with the question of who is most to blame for what they all have done. (By the way, Canby, the bartender, does end up comforting and caring for a lot of people who turned out to be incapable of making good choices, so that opening dialog turned out to be prophetic.)<br /> <br />In short, this is far more than the folksy Western I anticipated, and, alas, also more than a matter for armchair theorizing, or for dusty, overlooked classics.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18290353047464690426" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


