<div id="review_406330325" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/406330325" />
    <a title="Frances" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12402407-frances"><img alt="Frances" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346431542p2/12402407.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/406330325?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Frances" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Frances" href="/user/show/12402407-frances">Frances</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer406330325" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3207969759019560538">This book is horrifying - and rightly deserves a position in the canon of American literature. It depicts the definite dark-side of the American West mythos. Tillburg Clark creates characters to bear out the darkness, rather than employing abstract forces themselves. All that a man is, an outsider, an insider, a bully, a martyr, play in his decisions in this book. Though evil happens, it doesn&apos;t happen for evil&apos;s sake; rather, it happens because of the intersections and overlappings of the chara</span>
  <span id="freeText3207969759019560538" style="display:none">This book is horrifying - and rightly deserves a position in the canon of American literature. It depicts the definite dark-side of the American West mythos. Tillburg Clark creates characters to bear out the darkness, rather than employing abstract forces themselves. All that a man is, an outsider, an insider, a bully, a martyr, play in his decisions in this book. Though evil happens, it doesn't happen for evil's sake; rather, it happens because of the intersections and overlappings of the characters involved. Very well imagined, carefully written. It requires intellectual engagement with it; the plot does not necessarily speak volumes at its surface level, but it opens magnificently when the reader takes the time to wonder "why?". This is a book that engages "why?", not by pontificating, but by outlining circumstances and actions, leaving the reader to do the work. I have re-read this book multiple times, and it still speaks to me. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3207969759019560538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


