    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3069515435" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3069515435" />
    <a title="Williwaw" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3491750-williwaw"><img alt="Williwaw" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1304797883p2/3491750.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3069515435?book_show_action=true">Dec 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Williwaw" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Williwaw" href="/user/show/3491750-williwaw">Williwaw</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3069515435" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11766738835983009417">This is an excellent novel. Clark is especially good at concise descriptions of characters that are nevertheless surprisingly revealing and effective. His characters speak believably, and he describes scenes well. And he evokes the setting (small town Nevada, near the Sierras) as only someone who has experienced it could evoke it.<br/><br/>The first half of the novel is a bit on the slow side. People seem to have a hard time making up their minds and there&apos;s lots of back and forth amongst the town-folk ab</span>
  <span id="freeText11766738835983009417" style="display:none">This is an excellent novel. Clark is especially good at concise descriptions of characters that are nevertheless surprisingly revealing and effective. His characters speak believably, and he describes scenes well. And he evokes the setting (small town Nevada, near the Sierras) as only someone who has experienced it could evoke it.<br /><br />The first half of the novel is a bit on the slow side. People seem to have a hard time making up their minds and there's lots of back and forth amongst the town-folk about whether to take action against some purported cattle rustlers/killers who have gone on the lam.<br /><br />But once the story gets moving, there's a sense of inevitable momentum, and the madness of the mob is portrayed in a most compelling way. <br /><br />All the fine detail, from the muddy roads, to firelight flickering between trees, to the expressions on the faces of men about to die, struck me as utterly authentic. <br /><br />I decided to read this novel after noticing that another one by Clark was listed in, of all things, Horror: 100 Best Books (Jones &amp; Newman, eds.). There, Robert McCammon gushes about Track of the Cat. I wanted to read it, but didn't have a copy on hand, so I decided to read The Ox-Bow Incident while I'm on the hunt for a copy of Track of the Cat. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11766738835983009417" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


