<div id="review_2700206734" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2700206734" />
    <a title="Shawn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1926890-shawn"><img alt="Shawn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553962748p2/1926890.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2700206734?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Shawn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Shawn" href="/user/show/1926890-shawn">Shawn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1926890-shawn?shelf=objectionable-content-profanity">objectionable-content-profanity</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1926890-shawn?shelf=objectionable-content-violence">objectionable-content-violence</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2700206734" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13767496901683341309">It wouldn&apos;t be quite right to say I loved it, but I view it as a masterpiece. I recall this book being on the bookshelf at home when I was growing up, though with a very different cover that didn&apos;t entice me to read it then. But I picked it up now because I remembered seeing it growing up, and without knowing any more about it I dug into it. And once I felt swept up in it I didn&apos;t want to stop reading. It didn&apos;t know it was a &quot;Western,&quot; and in most ways I would say it isn&apos;t that at all (kind of </span>
  <span id="freeText13767496901683341309" style="display:none">It wouldn't be quite right to say I loved it, but I view it as a masterpiece. I recall this book being on the bookshelf at home when I was growing up, though with a very different cover that didn't entice me to read it then. But I picked it up now because I remembered seeing it growing up, and without knowing any more about it I dug into it. And once I felt swept up in it I didn't want to stop reading. It didn't know it was a "Western," and in most ways I would say it isn't that at all (kind of like how I feel about the film Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid, incidentally). It reminded me most acutely of the film 12 Angry Men, but in a frontier setting. Anyone who might feel unexcited by this book because they aren't into Westerns should reconsider. Many of the issues and feelings characterized in the book are things that are relevant to situations in my own life, such as current situations at work or political issues of the day, and I think that allowed it to draw out my own thoughts and emotions even more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13767496901683341309" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


